"""
mkt-context: Psalms 107-110
Chapters: 107-110 (93 missing verses; Ps 110:1 already present)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-psalms-107-110.py

Key context decisions:
- Psalm 107: Four-vignette structure (wilderness/prisoners/sick/sailors); wisdom conclusion v43;
  each refrain links to chesed; maritime imagery unique in Psalter
- Psalm 108: Composite psalm combining Ps 57:7-11 + Ps 60:5-12; geographic catalog of tribal
  territories; v12 vain-salvation principle; ANE sandal-casting ownership ritual (v9)
- Psalm 109: Imprecatory lament; vv6-19 quoted as enemy curses (many commentators);
  v8 cited in Acts 1:20 re: Judas; satan as legal accuser; v31 YHWH at right hand of needy
- Psalm 110: Most-cited OT text in NT; Melchizedek priesthood (v4) = Hebrews 5-7;
  king at YHWH's right hand (v1, already present) vs YHWH at king's right (v5)
"""
import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    # INTENT: merge without overwriting any verse already present in existing
    # CHANGE? Do not alter the guard; concurrent agents depend on append-only behavior
    # VERIFY: run twice; second run should report identical byte count for psalms.json
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NEW_DATA = {"107": {"1": "<p><b>Ps 107: The Great Thanksgiving Psalm — Four Rescues, One Refrain.</b> Ps 107 opens Book V of the Psalter with a joyful, liturgical thanksgiving that moves through four vignettes of divine rescue. Each section follows the same narrative arc: danger → cry to YHWH → rescue → thanksgiving refrain. The four groups (wilderness wanderers, vv4-9; prisoners, vv10-16; the sick, vv17-22; sailors in a storm, vv23-32) may represent types of exilic and post-exilic experience. The refrain 'O give thanks to the LORD, for he is good, for his steadfast love endures forever' (<i>ki tov ki leolam chasdo</i>) is the great liturgical formula of Israel's worship (1 Chr 16:34; Pss 106:1; 118:1; 136 passim). The formula is not merely doxological — it anchors the thanksgiving in the covenant term <i>chesed</i>: YHWH's loyal, covenant-obligated love is what makes every rescue possible.</p>", "2": "<p><b>'Let the redeemed of the LORD say so, whom he has redeemed from trouble'</b> — <i>yomeru geulei YHWH</i> (let the redeemed of the LORD say so). The 'redeemed' (<i>geulim</i>) are those who have been <i>ga'al</i>-ed — redeemed through the kinsman-redeemer mechanism (the <i>go'el</i>: the nearest relative who pays the price to buy back a family member from debt-slavery or captivity). YHWH as the divine <i>go'el</i> is a major theological motif of Isa 40-55 (Isa 41:14; 43:1; 44:22-24; 54:5). The 'trouble' (<i>tzar</i>, adversity/distress) from which they are redeemed echoes the Egyptian bondage. The command to 'say so' is a liturgical mandate: the rescued community is obligated to public testimony.</p>", "3": "<p><b>'...and gathered in from the lands, from the east and from the west, from the north and from the south'</b> — the four-direction gathering is the post-exilic ingathering formula (Isa 43:5-6: 'I will bring your offspring from the east... from the west... from the north... from the south'). The LXX adds 'and from the sea' (cf. Ps 107:23-32). This verse locates Ps 107 in the post-exilic context: the 'redeemed' are specifically those gathered from the Diaspora nations where they had been scattered by the Assyrian and Babylonian deportations.</p>", "4": "<p><b>'Some wandered in desert wastes, finding no way to a city to dwell in'</b> — the first vignette: wilderness wanderers. 'Desert wastes' (<i>midbar yeshimon</i>) — the same language as the Sinai wilderness (Deut 32:10: 'He found him in a desert land and in the howling waste of the wilderness'). The 'city to dwell in' (<i>ir moshav</i>) — the settled, inhabited place that the wanderer cannot find. This is the exile's experience: scattered from the homeland, wandering without a city of rest.</p>", "5": "<p><b>'Hungry and thirsty, their soul fainted within them'</b> — the physical extremity of the wilderness: <i>reevim vegam tzemaim</i> (hungry and also thirsty). The Exodus parallels: Exod 16 (hunger: the manna) and Exod 17 (thirst: Meribah water). The 'fainted soul' (<i>naphsham titateeph</i>) is the near-death exhaustion of prolonged deprivation. The soul (<i>naphesh</i>) — here the seat of bodily life and appetite — is failing.</p>", "6": "<p><b>'Then they cried to the LORD in their trouble, and he delivered them from their distress'</b> — the first occurrence of the rescue formula (<i>vayitze'aqu el-YHWH batzar lahem mimetzukoteihem yatziltem</i>). The cry (<i>tza'aq</i>) is the emergency summons — the same verb used for Israel's cry from Egyptian bondage (Exod 2:23). The divine response: 'he delivered them' (<i>yatziltem</i>, Hiphil of <i>natzal</i>, to snatch from danger). The rescue is immediate — no delay once the cry goes up.</p>", "7": "<p><b>'He led them by a straight way till they reached a city to dwell in'</b> — the divine guidance: <i>derekh yeshara</i> (a straight/direct way) — in contrast to the wandering of vv4-5. The 'city to dwell in' — now they reach what they had failed to find. The Exodus pattern: YHWH led Israel through the wilderness by the pillar of cloud and fire (Exod 13:21) on a path that the wanderers alone could not find. The second Exodus (return from exile) follows the same pattern (Isa 40:3; 43:19).</p>", "8": "<p><b>'Let them thank the LORD for his steadfast love, for his wondrous works to the children of man!'</b> — the first occurrence of the thanksgiving refrain (also at vv15, 21, 31). The congregation is summoned to thank (<i>yodu</i>, Hiphil of <i>yadah</i>, to give public acknowledgment/thanksgiving) YHWH for both his <i>chesed</i> (steadfast/covenant love) and his <i>niphlaot</i> (wondrous works). The two grounds of thanksgiving are YHWH's character (<i>chesed</i>) and YHWH's acts (<i>niphlaot</i>).</p>", "9": "<p><b>'For he satisfies the longing soul, and the hungry soul he fills with good things'</b> — the specific content of the rescue: provision for physical need. 'Longing soul' (<i>naphesh shaqeqah</i>) — the soul that thirsts intensely — satisfied (<i>savet</i>, given its fill). 'The hungry soul' (<i>naphesh reevah</i>) filled with 'good things' (<i>tov</i>). The satisfaction language echoes Ps 103:5 ('who satisfies you with good so that your youth is renewed like the eagle's'). The physical provision is also spiritual fulfillment — the whole person is addressed.</p>", "10": "<p><b>'Some sat in darkness and in the shadow of death, prisoners in affliction and in irons'</b> — the second vignette: prisoners. 'Shadow of death' (<i>tzalmavet</i>) — the deep darkness of the underworld or of mortal danger; cf. Ps 23:4. 'Affliction and in irons' (<i>oni uvarzel</i>) — captivity imagery: the iron fetters of the prisoner. In the ANE, prisoners were kept in underground dungeons and bound with bronze or iron chains. This vignette maps onto the Babylonian exile: the deportees imprisoned in a foreign land under foreign law.</p>", "11": "<p><b>'For they had rebelled against the words of God, and spurned the counsel of the Most High'</b> — the moral cause of their captivity: rebellion (<i>maru</i>, Piel of <i>marah</i>) against 'the words of God' (<i>imrei El</i>) and contempt for 'the counsel of the Most High' (<i>atzat Elyon</i>). The exile is not merely a geopolitical catastrophe but a covenantal consequence: the prophets had warned, the people had rejected the warning, and the Babylonian captivity was the curse of Deut 28:36-37 ('the LORD will bring you and your king to a nation neither you nor your fathers have known').</p>", "12": "<p><b>'So he bowed their hearts down with hard labor; they fell down, with none to help'</b> — the hardship of captivity: <i>vayachna beamal libbam</i> (he humbled their heart with labor). YHWH himself is the agent of the humiliation — the captivity is the divine rod of discipline. 'Fell down with none to help' (<i>koshlu vein ozer</i>) — the characteristic desolation of the abandoned: no human helper, the vacuum that makes the divine rescue uniquely meaningful.</p>", "13": "<p><b>'Then they cried to the LORD in their trouble, and he delivered them from their distress'</b> — the rescue formula (second occurrence). The pattern holds even for those whose captivity was their own fault (v11): the divine responsiveness to the cry (<i>tza'aq</i>) is not conditioned on the righteousness of the crier. This is a key theological point — YHWH hears even the disciplined rebel who returns to cry out.</p>", "14": "<p><b>'He brought them out of darkness and the shadow of death, and burst their bonds apart'</b> — the rescue from captivity: 'brought them out of darkness' (<i>yotziim mechoshech</i>) echoes the Exodus language (Exod 20:2: 'I am the LORD who brought you out of Egypt'). 'Burst their bonds apart' (<i>umosroteihem ynateq</i>) — the severing of the iron fetters. The prison liberation anticipates the NT image of Christ as the one who sets captives free (Isa 61:1; Luke 4:18; John 8:36).</p>", "15": "<p><b>'Let them thank the LORD for his steadfast love, for his wondrous works to the children of man!'</b> — the refrain (second). The wondrous works (<i>niphlaot</i>) for the second group are liberation from imprisonment: the divine power to break physical chains. The 'children of man' (<i>bene adam</i>) includes all humanity — YHWH's rescue is not restricted to Israel but the psalm's primary reference is the covenant people.</p>", "16": "<p><b>'For he shatters the doors of bronze and cuts in two the bars of iron'</b> — 'doors of bronze' (<i>daltot nechoshet</i>) and 'bars of iron' (<i>brichei barzel</i>) — the strongest ANE prison materials. Isa 45:2 applies identical language to YHWH's action through Cyrus: 'I will break in pieces the doors of bronze and cut through the bars of iron.' The psalmist may have this Isaianic text in mind: the Persian liberation of the Jews from Babylonian captivity as YHWH shattering the prison doors.</p>", "17": "<p><b>'Some were fools through their sinful ways, and because of their iniquities suffered affliction'</b> — the third vignette: the sick. 'Fools' (<i>evilim</i>) — those who act without wisdom or covenant understanding, not merely intellectually deficient but morally foolish. Their sickness is directly tied to their 'sinful ways' (<i>derekh pesha'am</i>) and 'iniquities' (<i>avonot</i>): the OT connection between sin and sickness is a theological principle (Ps 38:3-5; John 9:2-3 must be read against this background, where Jesus complicates the simple equation).</p>", "18": "<p><b>'They loathed any kind of food, and they drew near to the gates of death'</b> — the sickness's physical extremity: 'loathed any kind of food' (<i>kol ochel tetalev naphsham</i>) — the appetite for life itself is gone. 'Gates of death' (<i>sha'are mavet</i>) — the ANE imagery of death as a city with gates into Sheol; cf. Isa 38:10; Matt 16:18. The sick person has approached to the threshold of the underworld.</p>", "19": "<p><b>'Then they cried to the LORD in their trouble, and he delivered them from their distress'</b> — the rescue formula (third occurrence). The same pattern: even those whose suffering arose from their own foolishness cry out and YHWH responds. The rescue formula's repetition without qualification shows that the divine rescuing does not require the petitioner to have been innocent — only that they cry to YHWH.</p>", "20": "<p><b>'He sent out his word and healed them, and delivered them from their destruction'</b> — 'He sent out his word' (<i>yishlach devaro</i>) — the divine word as healing agent. YHWH's healing comes through his spoken word: the same word by which he created (Gen 1) also heals and restores. The 'word' (<i>dabar</i>) that heals here becomes, in the NT, the Word who takes flesh (John 1:1-14) and heals by his presence. Matt 8:8 (the centurion: 'only say the word') connects to this tradition.</p>", "21": "<p><b>'Let them thank the LORD for his steadfast love, for his wondrous works to the children of man!'</b> — the refrain (third). The wondrous work for this group is healing — the divine word's power over sickness. The refrain's repetition builds momentum toward the fourth and climactic vignette.</p>", "22": "<p><b>'And let them offer sacrifices of thanksgiving, and tell of his deeds in songs of joy!'</b> — the liturgical response to healing: 'sacrifices of thanksgiving' (<i>zivchei todah</i>) — the specific category of peace-offering made in fulfilment of a vow after deliverance from danger (Lev 7:12-15). The <i>todah</i> sacrifice required the whole community to eat together, accompanied by specific types of unleavened bread. The public 'songs of joy' (<i>berinanah yesapperu</i>) are the verbal testimony accompanying the sacrifice. Healing demands both liturgical and verbal response.</p>", "23": "<p><b>'Some went down to the sea in ships, doing business on the great waters'</b> — the fourth vignette: sailors. This is the only maritime passage in the Psalter (Pss 93 and 29 reference the sea symbolically; this is actual maritime commerce). The ancient Mediterranean trade routes: 'going down to the sea in ships' (<i>yordei hayam be'oniyot</i>) was the description of Phoenician and coastal merchants whose livelihoods depended on sea-voyages. The 'great waters' (<i>mayim rabbim</i>) — the cosmological term for the chaotic waters over which YHWH has sovereignty.</p>", "24": "<p><b>'They saw the deeds of the LORD, his wondrous works in the deep'</b> — the sailors have a unique vantage point: they see YHWH's wondrous works (<i>niphlaot</i>) specifically 'in the deep' (<i>bametzulah</i>). The deep (<i>metzulah</i>) is the furthest reach of the sea — the abyssal realm where YHWH's power is most dramatically visible to those who venture there.</p>", "25": "<p><b>'For he commanded and raised the stormy wind, which lifted up the waves of the sea'</b> — YHWH commands (<i>yetzav</i>) the storm wind (<i>ruach searah</i>): the storm is not natural disaster but divine action. The 'lifting up' (<i>varomer galav</i>) of the waves — the sea's waves under divine control. Ps 29 describes the same storm-YHWH theology. The ANE background: Baal was the storm-god in Ugaritic mythology; Israel's psalm claims the storm for YHWH.</p>", "26": "<p><b>'They mounted up to heaven; they went down to the depths; their courage melted away in their evil plight'</b> — the sailors' terrifying experience: 'mounted up to heaven' — the ship cresting a wave; 'went down to the depths' (<i>yerdeu tehomot</i>) — plunging into the trough. The alternation creates dread. 'Their courage melted away' (<i>naphsham beraah titmogeg</i>, their soul melted in their distress) — the visceral fear response.</p>", "27": "<p><b>'They reeled and staggered like drunken men and were at their wits' end'</b> — 'reeled and staggered like drunken men' (<i>yachoggu veyanu'u kashikkor</i>) — the rolling of the ship makes the sailors appear drunk: a striking maritime observation of the effects of rough seas. 'Wits' end' (<i>kol chochmatam titballa</i>, all their wisdom was swallowed up) — their navigational skill and seamanship, all their expertise, is consumed by the storm they cannot control.</p>", "28": "<p><b>'Then they cried to the LORD in their trouble, and he delivered them from their distress'</b> — the rescue formula (fourth and final occurrence). Even the sailors — not a group typically associated with covenantal piety — cry to YHWH and receive deliverance. The formula's applicability to all four groups regardless of cause or occupation makes it universal: anyone in extremity who cries to YHWH receives his response.</p>", "29": "<p><b>'He made the storm be still, and the waves of the sea were hushed'</b> — 'made the storm be still' (<i>yaqem searah lidemamah</i>) — the storm that YHWH commanded (v25) is now stilled by his word. The sea's waves 'hushed' (<i>vayehechashu galehem</i>). This direct antecedent of Mark 4:39 ('Peace! Be still!') — Jesus calming the storm uses the same divine prerogative. The disciples' question 'Who then is this?' (Mark 4:41) is answered by recognizing YHWH's storm-command in Ps 107.</p>", "30": "<p><b>'Then they were glad that the waters were quiet, and he brought them to their desired haven'</b> — 'glad that the waters were quiet' (<i>vayishmchu ki yishtaquu</i>) — the joy of relief after terror. 'Their desired haven' (<i>el mehoz chephtzam</i>, to the harbor of their desire) — the safe harbor that was their destination. The ANE image of the harbor as safety and rest: the homeport after the dangerous voyage is the metaphor for covenant rest and the promised land.</p>", "31": "<p><b>'Let them thank the LORD for his steadfast love, for his wondrous works to the children of man!'</b> — the refrain (fourth), now amplified by the full preceding narrative. The wondrous work for the sailors is storm-stilling — the most dramatic of the four rescues because the threat was entirely outside human control. The <i>chesed</i> that governs all four vignettes is now fully displayed.</p>", "32": "<p><b>'Let them extol him in the congregation of the people, and praise him in the assembly of the elders'</b> — the thanksgiving testimony moves to two settings: 'the congregation of the people' (<i>qahal am</i>) — the full assembly — and 'the assembly of the elders' (<i>moshav zeqenim</i>) — the governing council. Both venues are required: the sailors' testimony is not merely private devotion but a public matter affecting the community's understanding of YHWH.</p>", "33": "<p><b>'He turns rivers into a desert, springs of water into thirsty ground'</b> — the psalm's second half (vv33-43) shifts from the four vignettes to creation-scale divine sovereignty. YHWH is the lord of hydrological transformation: the productive made barren. This is the covenant curse dynamic (Deut 28:23-24: 'the sky over your head shall be bronze, and the earth under you shall be iron') — YHWH's judgment turns fertile land into desert.</p>", "34": "<p><b>'...a fruitful land into a salty waste, because of the evil of its inhabitants'</b> — 'fruitful land' (<i>eretz periyah</i>) into 'salty waste' (<i>melechah</i>) — the salting of land as permanent agricultural destruction (Judg 9:45: Abimelech salted Shechem; Deut 29:23 describes Sodom's salt and sulfur). 'Because of the evil of its inhabitants' (<i>mera'at yoshevim bah</i>) — the explicit covenant-judgment logic: human moral failure produces ecological devastation.</p>", "35": "<p><b>'He turns a desert into pools of water, a parched land into springs of water'</b> — the reverse transformation: barren made fertile. The pair of vv33-34 and vv35-38 shows YHWH's complete sovereignty over both directions: he can curse the productive and bless the barren. Isa 41:18 uses identical imagery for the second Exodus: 'I will make the wilderness a pool of water, and the dry land springs of water.'</p>", "36": "<p><b>'And there he lets the hungry dwell, and they establish a city to dwell in'</b> — the 'hungry' (<i>reevim</i>) from v5 return: those who could not find a 'city to dwell in' (v4) are now settled and establish one. The wilderness wanderers of the first vignette find their city; the barren land produces their settlement. The circling back to vignette-one language unifies the psalm.</p>", "37": "<p><b>'They sow fields and plant vineyards and get a fruitful yield'</b> — agricultural restoration: the covenant blessings of Deut 28:4 ('blessed shall be the fruit of your womb and the fruit of your ground') manifest in the post-exilic return. The planting of vineyards is the symbol of long-term settlement and security (Jer 29:5: 'plant gardens and eat their produce' — Jeremiah's command to the exiles to settle in Babylon precisely because the exile will be long).</p>", "38": "<p><b>'By his blessing they multiply greatly, and he does not let their livestock diminish'</b> — the covenant multiplication blessing (Deut 28:4: 'blessed shall be the fruit of your womb and the fruit of your livestock'). The community's growth in number is a sign of divine favor and covenant restoration. The livestock's health is a marker of agricultural prosperity in the ancient economy.</p>", "39": "<p><b>'When they are diminished and brought low through oppression, evil, and sorrow'</b> — the turn to adversity: the same community that flourished (vv36-38) can be diminished (<i>yimate'u</i>) through oppression (<i>otzer</i>), evil (<i>ra'ah</i>), and sorrow (<i>yagon</i>). The YHWH who blessed also allows reversal. This verse functions as a hinge: the two possible trajectories for the covenant community.</p>", "40": "<p><b>'He pours contempt on princes and makes them wander in trackless wastes'</b> — YHWH's judgment on the powerful: 'pours contempt on princes' (<i>shophekh buz al-nedivim</i>) — the divine reversal of human status. The nobles (<i>nedivim</i>) who held power are humiliated. 'Wander in trackless wastes' (<i>yata'em bivohu lo-darech</i>) — the wilderness wandering as judgment: the princes who oppressed the humble find themselves in the pathless desert. Job 12:24 uses identical language for YHWH's sovereign overturning of human power.</p>", "41": "<p><b>'But he raises up the needy out of affliction and makes their families like flocks'</b> — the reversal: 'raises up the needy' (<i>yesagev evyon meoni</i>) — the divine exaltation of the humble (1 Sam 2:8: Hannah's song; Luke 1:52-53: Mary's Magnificat). 'Families like flocks' (<i>mishpachot katzzon</i>) — the restored family's fertility mirroring the growth of sheep. The divine preference for the needy over the powerful is a consistent covenant-theology theme.</p>", "42": "<p><b>'The upright see it and are glad, and all wickedness shuts its mouth'</b> — the two responses to YHWH's reversals: the upright (<i>yesharim</i>) see and rejoice (<i>veyismachu</i>); the wicked (<i>kol-avlah</i>, all wickedness) have nothing to say — their mouths are shut (<i>qapetza piha</i>). The rhetorical reversal: human wisdom (represented by the princes of v40) is silenced by YHWH's judgment; the wisdom of those who fear YHWH is vindicated.</p>", "43": "<p><b>'Whoever is wise, let him attend to these things; let them consider the steadfast love of the LORD'</b> — the wisdom conclusion. The psalm, which began with liturgical thanksgiving, ends with sapiential reflection: the wise person (<i>mi chacham</i>) attends (<i>veyishmor</i>, guards/keeps) to the patterns described and 'considers' (<i>veyitbonenu</i>, from <i>binah</i>, understanding) the <i>chasde YHWH</i> (the steadfast love-acts of YHWH). The four vignettes and the cosmic sovereignty of vv33-42 become material for wisdom meditation. The psalm integrates praise, narrative, and wisdom genres.</p>"}, "108": {"1": "<p><b>Ps 108: Composite Psalm — Confidence in YHWH's Faithfulness for Battle.</b> Ps 108 is a liturgical compilation that combines Ps 57:7-11 (= Ps 108:1-5) and Ps 60:5-12 (= Ps 108:6-13). The phenomenon of combining portions of earlier psalms into a new composition is attested in the Psalter (cf. Ps 135 drawing from multiple sources). The new context changes the meaning: taken from their individual lament settings and combined, the doxological section (vv1-5) is placed in service of a national military petition (vv6-13). 'My heart is steadfast, O God! I will sing and make melody with all my being!' (<i>nacon libbi Elohim, ashirah va'azamerah af kevodi</i>) — the firm resolve of the worshiper. 'Glory' (<i>kavod</i>) as the organ of praise — the psalmist's weightiest, most dignified capacity will praise.</p>", "2": "<p><b>'Awake, O harp and lyre! I will awake the dawn!'</b> — <i>urah hanevel vekinor</i> (awake, O lute and harp!) — the musical instruments addressed as if sleeping, summoned to wakefulness for early morning worship. 'I will awake the dawn' (<i>a'irah shachar</i>) — the psalmist rises before dawn to begin praise: the paradox of waking the dawn by beginning worship before it arrives. This early morning devotion is also in Ps 5:3; 59:16; 63:1.</p>", "3": "<p><b>'I will give thanks to you, O LORD, among the peoples; I will sing praises to you among the nations'</b> — the universal audience of the praise: 'among the peoples' (<i>vaadim</i>) and 'among the nations' (<i>bale'umim</i>). The individual's thanksgiving reaches beyond Israel to all peoples — an anticipation of the universal praise of Ps 117 and the NT mission's rationale (Rom 15:9-11 cites such Psalms to establish the Gentile mission).</p>", "4": "<p><b>'For your steadfast love is great above the heavens; your faithfulness reaches to the clouds'</b> — 'great above the heavens' (<i>gadol meal shamayim chasdecha</i>) — the <i>chesed</i> of YHWH exceeds even the immensity of the heavens. 'Faithfulness reaches to the clouds' (<i>vead shechaqim amitecha</i>) — <i>emet</i> (faithfulness/truth) measured in atmospheric distance. The two covenant qualities (<i>chesed</i> and <i>emet</i>) that appeared together in Ps 85:10 (where they 'meet') are here measured cosmologically: they surpass and fill all created space.</p>", "5": "<p><b>'Be exalted, O God, above the heavens! Let your glory be over all the earth!'</b> — the doxological petition: 'be exalted above the heavens' (<i>rumah al hashamayim Elohim</i>) — even the measure of v4 (your <i>chesed</i> is above the heavens) leads to the petition that YHWH himself be exalted above his own attributes' measure. 'Your glory over all the earth' (<i>veal kol haaretz kevodecha</i>) — the universal scope of the divine glory-claim.</p>", "6": "<p><b>'That your beloved ones may be rescued; give salvation by your right hand and answer us!'</b> — the transition from doxology to petition. 'Your beloved ones' (<i>yedidecha</i>) — the covenant-beloved, Israel. The 'right hand' (<i>yeminecha</i>) — YHWH's power-hand, the instrument of military rescue. The petition grounds the rescue request in the doxology: the God whose <i>chesed</i> exceeds the heavens is the one being asked to apply that <i>chesed</i> to the national crisis.</p>", "7": "<p><b>'God has promised in his holiness: I will exult, I will divide up Shechem and portion out the Valley of Succoth'</b> — the divine oracle (from Ps 60:6-8). The specific geography: Shechem (central highlands, the ancient covenant-assembly site: Gen 33:18-20; Josh 24) and the Valley of Succoth (Transjordan, east of the Jordan). YHWH's claim over these territories — divided between the tribal allotments — is the basis of the petition. The land belongs to YHWH and was allocated by him.</p>", "8": "<p><b>'Gilead is mine; Manasseh is mine; Ephraim is my helmet; Judah is my scepter'</b> — the tribal catalog: Gilead (Transjordan territory of the Reubenites, Gadites, and half-tribe of Manasseh), Manasseh (half in Transjordan, half in Cisjordan), Ephraim ('my helmet' — the major military tribe of the north; <i>rosh Ephraim</i>, the head/foremost of the northern tribes), Judah ('my scepter' — the royal tribe, the seat of Davidic authority). YHWH speaks of the tribes as his possessions and instruments.</p>", "9": "<p><b>'Moab is my washbasin; over Edom I cast my shoe; over Philistia I shout in triumph'</b> — the catalog continues with subjugated nations: Moab as 'washbasin' (<i>sir rachtziy</i>) — the basin into which dirty water is thrown, a symbol of contemptible servitude. Edom: YHWH 'casts his shoe' (<i>al-Edom ashlikh na'ali</i>) — claiming ownership (Ruth 4:7: removing or throwing a sandal was a property-transfer symbol). Philistia: 'I shout in triumph' (<i>hitroha'i</i>, Hithpolel of <i>rua</i>). All three traditional enemies are subjected to YHWH's authority.</p>", "10": "<p><b>'Who will bring me into the fortified city? Who will lead me to Edom?'</b> — the psalmist's question arising from the oracle: if YHWH has declared ownership of all these territories (vv7-9), why is Edom's 'fortified city' (<i>ir matzor</i>, probably Petra/Sela, the rock-fortress of Edom) still beyond reach? The gap between the divine declaration of ownership and the human military reality is the psalm's tension. Knowing YHWH owns Edom does not automatically open the campaign route.</p>", "11": "<p><b>'Have you not rejected us, O God? You do not go out, O God, with our armies'</b> — the lament beneath the confidence: 'have you not rejected us?' (<i>halo attah Elohim zenavtanu</i>) — the complaint that YHWH's presence with the army has been withdrawn. The military theology of Israel: YHWH goes out with Israel's armies as the divine warrior (Num 10:35: 'Arise, O LORD, and let your enemies be scattered'; 1 Sam 4:3-11 — the tragedy when the ark's presence does not guarantee victory). The oracle (vv7-9) was the declaration of divine ownership; the lament (v11) is the gap in actual experience.</p>", "12": "<p><b>'Oh grant us help against the foe, for vain is the salvation of man!'</b> — 'vain is the salvation of man' (<i>shav teshu'at adam</i>) — the key theological principle of Ps 108: human military power alone accomplishes nothing. The only efficacious help (<i>ezrat</i>) must come from YHWH. This is the military theology of Ps 20:7 ('some trust in chariots and some in horses, but we trust in the name of the LORD our God').</p>", "13": "<p><b>'With God we shall do valiantly; it is he who will tread down our foes'</b> — the psalm's conclusion in confident faith: <i>be-Elohim na'aseh chayil</i> (with God we will do powerfully/valiantly). The victory is neither automatic (the oracle does not guarantee military ease) nor human (the lament of v11 shows the limits of human effort) but covenantal: 'with God' the enemies are trodden down. The final word is YHWH's agency, not Israel's.</p>"}, "109": {"1": "<p><b>Ps 109: David's Imprecatory Lament — The Accusation Against the False Accuser.</b> Ps 109 is the most sustained imprecatory psalm in the Psalter and among the most theologically difficult. David prays in response to a false accusation: someone has brought charges against him that are both wicked and unjust (vv2-5). The central section (vv6-19) is the longest imprecatory passage in the Psalter — David either quotes his enemy's accusations back to them (interpreting vv6-19 as the enemy's words against David, which many commentators adopt) or prays these curses directly against his accuser. NT application: Acts 1:20 cites v8 ('let another take his office') with reference to Judas Iscariot. 'O God of my praise, do not keep silence!' — the appeal to YHWH as 'my praise' (<i>Elohai tehillati</i>) — the God who has been the object and source of David's praise is asked not to be silent in the face of false accusation.</p>", "2": "<p><b>'For wicked and deceitful mouths are opened against me, speaking against me with lying tongues'</b> — the triple characterization of the accusation: 'wicked mouths' (<i>pe rasha</i>), 'deceitful mouths' (<i>pe mirmah</i>), and 'lying tongues' (<i>leshon sheqer</i>). The speech-crime: false accusation in a legal context. In the ANE judicial system, legal proceedings depended on testimony. A false witness (<i>ed shaqer</i>) was a grave moral violation (Exod 20:16; Deut 19:16-21 prescribes the death penalty for false witnesses).</p>", "3": "<p><b>'They encircle me with words of hate, and attack me without cause'</b> — 'encircle me' (<i>vayasovuvuni</i>) — the corporate plurality of the accusers surrounding the psalmist. 'Without cause' (<i>chinnam</i>) — the same term as Ps 35:7; 69:4; Job 2:3: innocent suffering. The <i>chinnam</i> suffering is the theological problem: why does YHWH allow his servant to suffer unjust accusation?</p>", "4": "<p><b>'In return for my love they accuse me, but I give myself to prayer'</b> — 'in return for my love' (<i>tachat ahavati</i>) — the enemy's hostility is the response to David's love; the accusation is the return for his covenant loyalty. 'I give myself to prayer' (<i>va-ani tephillah</i>, and I am prayer) — David's response to false accusation is not counter-accusation but prayer. The prayer-posture as the only recourse against unjust power.</p>", "5": "<p><b>'So they reward me evil for good, and hatred for my love'</b> — the inversion of covenant loyalty: evil for good (<i>ra tachat tovah</i>) and hatred for love (<i>sinah tachat ahavati</i>). The covenant community was supposed to model <i>chesed</i> — loyal love within the community. The accuser has violated the fundamental social fabric of covenant life by repaying love with hate.</p>", "6": "<p><b>'Appoint a wicked man against him; let an accuser stand at his right hand'</b> — at v6 the perspective shifts (or is quoted). Many interpreters take vv6-19 as David quoting his enemies' curses against him (i.e., 'they say, appoint a wicked man against him'). On this reading, the imprecations are the enemy's curses that David is bringing before YHWH for vindication. 'An accuser' (<i>satan</i>) — the <i>satan</i> here is a legal term for the adversary/prosecutor in a court proceeding (cf. Zech 3:1-2; Job 1-2). The accuser stands at the right hand — the position of the legal advocate or accuser in ANE court procedure.</p>", "7": "<p><b>'When he is tried, let him come forth guilty; let his prayer be counted as sin!'</b> — 'let him come forth guilty' (<i>yetzeh rasha</i>) — the wish that the trial produce condemnation. 'Let his prayer be counted as sin' (<i>utephilato tihyeh lachata'ah</i>) — the most devastating curse: that even his appeals to YHWH be regarded as sin rather than as piety. The contrast with David's prayer (v4: 'I give myself to prayer') is stark: the righteous pray and are heard; the guilty pray and are condemned.</p>", "8": "<p><b>'May his days be few; may another take his office!'</b> — 'his days be few' (<i>yihyu yamav me'atim</i>) — a brief life as covenant curse (Deut 28:20: 'until you perish quickly'). 'Let another take his office' (<i>pequdato yiqach acher</i>) — the PKD-root (<i>pequdah</i>) refers to his appointed position, his office of oversight. Acts 1:20 cites this verse directly in the context of replacing Judas Iscariot among the Twelve: the apostolic 'office' must be filled by another because Judas's days were cut short by his own sin.</p>", "9": "<p><b>'May his children be fatherless and his wife a widow!'</b> — the covenant curse on descendants (Exod 20:5: visiting iniquity on children). The making of wife and children into widow and orphans — the two most vulnerable categories in the covenant legal system — by the accuser's death is the extension of the curse to his household. The irony: the accuser has endangered David's household; the curse returns that danger to the accuser's household.</p>", "10": "<p><b>'May his children wander about and beg, seeking food far from the ruins of their homes!'</b> — 'wander about and beg' (<i>vanu venav venashalu</i>) — the children reduced to vagabondage. The specific shame of begging in the ANE: it indicated the complete loss of the patronage network and family land that gave identity and security. 'Far from the ruins of their homes' (<i>vedoreshu micharboteihem</i>) — even their ruins are not their own; they have no place even to make claim on the debris of what was their home.</p>", "11": "<p><b>'May the creditor seize all that he has; may strangers plunder the fruits of his toil!'</b> — 'the creditor seize all' (<i>yenaqesh nosheh lekhol asher-lo</i>) — debt-collection in the ANE could result in the confiscation of all assets, the enslavement of family members, and the loss of ancestral land. 'Strangers plunder' (<i>yavozzu zarim yegi'o</i>) — the loss even of labor's produce to foreigners: the covenant curse of Deut 28:33 ('a nation that you have not known shall eat up the fruit of your ground').</p>", "12": "<p><b>'Let there be none to extend kindness to him, nor any to pity his fatherless children!'</b> — 'none to extend kindness' (<i>al-yihi lo mosech chesed</i>) — no one to perform <i>chesed</i> (covenant-loyal kindness) toward him or his children. The removal of <i>chesed</i> from the covenant community is the most complete social curse: without <i>chesed</i>, the individual has no network of obligation, no one who owes him loyalty. The fatherless children deserve pity (<i>chanunim</i>) by covenant law (Pss 82:3-4; 68:5) — the prayer that no one extend it is the inversion of covenant obligations.</p>", "13": "<p><b>'May his posterity be cut off; may his name be blotted out in the second generation!'</b> — 'posterity cut off' (<i>yikharet achariyt</i>) — the end of the family line. 'Name blotted out' (<i>yimach shemam</i>) — in the ANE, a person's name surviving through descendants was the primary form of immortality. Having the name 'blotted out' (<i>machah</i>) was the annihilation of legacy. Deut 29:20 uses identical language for the covenant curse on the most defiant rebel.</p>", "14": "<p><b>'May the iniquity of his fathers be remembered before the LORD, and let not the sin of his mother be blotted out!'</b> — the generational curse: the accumulated sin of the family line recalled before YHWH rather than forgiven. This is the application of the covenant warning (Exod 20:5: 'visiting the iniquity of the fathers on the children to the third and fourth generation of those who hate me'). The curse asks that no covenant forgiveness be extended to this family line.</p>", "15": "<p><b>'Let them be before the LORD continually, that he may cut off the memory of them from the earth!'</b> — the sins of the family before YHWH 'continually' (<i>tamid</i>) — always before the divine court, never forgiven or forgotten. The goal: the cutting off (<i>yikhrat</i>) of their memory (<i>zikram</i>) from the earth. The total annihilation of the family from the record of the living.</p>", "16": "<p><b>'For he did not remember to show kindness, but pursued the poor and needy and the brokenhearted, to put them to death'</b> — the judicial rationale for the curses: the accuser failed to show <i>chesed</i> (covenant kindness), and worse, actively 'pursued' (<i>radaph</i>) the vulnerable. 'The poor and needy and brokenhearted' (<i>ani ve'evyon unekeh levav</i>) — the triple-vulnerable class whom YHWH specifically protects. Pursuing them to death inverts the covenant mandate. The imprecation is proportional to the injustice.</p>", "17": "<p><b>'He loved to curse; let curses come upon him! He did not delight in blessing; may it be far from him!'</b> — the lex talionis logic of the curses: the accuser's love of cursing (<i>vaye'ehav qelalah</i>) returns as curses on himself. His rejection of blessing (<i>lo chaphettz bevarachah</i>) means blessing is removed from him. The moral logic: what one habitually does to others becomes one's own fate.</p>", "18": "<p><b>'He clothed himself with cursing as his coat; may it soak into his body like water, like oil into his bones!'</b> — the clothing metaphor: cursing as the accuser's garment — his defining characteristic, what he wears. The curse returns and penetrates: like water soaking through clothing into the body (<i>kammayim vayavo veqirbo</i>) and oil into the bones (<i>kashemen betzamotav</i>). The imagery of something entering the body and saturating it describes irreversible absorption: the curse becomes constitutive of the accuser's very being.</p>", "19": "<p><b>'May it be like a garment that he wraps around him, like a belt that he puts on every day!'</b> — the full clothing metaphor: the curse wraps around like a garment (<i>begad</i>) and is worn daily like a belt (<i>chagor</i>). The accuser's curse returns to him as permanent clothing — his identity is defined by it. The end of the long imprecatory section: everything the accuser projected onto David returns to him as his own fate.</p>", "20": "<p><b>'May this be the reward of my accusers from the LORD, of those who speak evil against my life!'</b> — David's explicit statement: the imprecatory section (vv6-19) is the 'reward' (<i>pe'ulat</i>, wages, the thing earned by one's work) from YHWH for those who falsely accused him. Whether the curses were David's own prayer or the enemy's curses being returned, this verse is David's clear endorsement: let YHWH render this justice against the false accusers.</p>", "21": "<p><b>'But you, O GOD my Lord, deal on my behalf for your name's sake; because your steadfast love is good, deliver me!'</b> — the shift from imprecation to personal petition. David addresses YHWH directly: 'deal on my behalf' (<i>ase iti</i>) for two reasons: (1) YHWH's 'name's sake' (<i>lema'an shemecha</i>) — the divine reputation is at stake if YHWH's servant is abandoned; (2) YHWH's 'steadfast love' (<i>chesed</i>) — the covenant quality that David has appealed to throughout. The <i>chesed</i> is described as 'good' (<i>tov chasdecha</i>) — not merely obligatory but genuinely benevolent.</p>", "22": "<p><b>'For I am poor and needy, and my heart is stricken within me'</b> — David's self-description: 'poor and needy' (<i>ani ve'evyon</i>) — the same double-term as v16 (those the accuser pursued). David now occupies the position of the vulnerable: he has become what the accuser targeted. 'Heart stricken within me' (<i>libbi chalal beqirbi</i>, my heart is pierced/wounded within me) — the interior wound of unjust accusation.</p>", "23": "<p><b>'I am gone like a shadow at evening; I am shaken off like a locust'</b> — two images of fragility: 'shadow at evening' (<i>ketzilal kintetot</i>, like the lengthening shadow of evening) — the shadow that stretches and disappears as light fades; 'shaken off like a locust' (<i>ninachti kearbe</i>, tossed off like a locust) — locusts brushed aside from clothing, unwanted and insignificant. David's sense of his own insignificance in the face of powerful accusers.</p>", "24": "<p><b>'My knees are weak through fasting; my body has become gaunt, with no fat'</b> — the physical effects of the crisis: fasting (<i>tzom</i>) — whether voluntary (in penitence or prayer) or involuntary (from persecution and anxiety). 'Gaunt with no fat' (<i>uchesari kikchash mipotza shamah</i>) — the wasting of the body under sustained stress. The physical description grounds the prayer in embodied suffering.</p>", "25": "<p><b>'I am an object of scorn to my accusers; when they see me, they wag their heads'</b> — 'object of scorn' (<i>vaa'ni hayyiti cherpah lahem</i>, I became a reproach to them) — the social dimension: not merely private suffering but public disgrace. 'Wag their heads' (<i>yanu'u rosham</i>) — the ANE gesture of contemptuous mockery (Ps 22:7: 'all who see me mock me; they make mouths at me; they wag their heads'). Jesus on the cross receives this same gesture (Matt 27:39).</p>", "26": "<p><b>'Help me, O LORD my God! Save me according to your steadfast love!'</b> — the naked petition: <i>ozreni YHWH Elohai</i> (help me, O LORD my God!) and <i>hoshi'eni kechasdecha</i> (save me according to your steadfast love). The two divine names — the covenant name YHWH and the personal <i>Elohai</i> (my God) — are combined with the prayer for salvation grounded in <i>chesed</i>. After the long imprecatory section, this verse is the concentrated prayer.</p>", "27": "<p><b>'Let them know that this is your hand; you, O LORD, have done it!'</b> — the purpose of the rescue: that the false accusers and observers will recognize the rescue as YHWH's doing (<i>yadah ki yadecha zot attah YHWH asitah</i>). The recognition-formula (that they may know) from the Exodus tradition is now applied to the personal vindication: the same YHWH who made Egypt 'know' his power at the sea will make David's accusers 'know' his power in vindicating his servant.</p>", "28": "<p><b>'Let them curse, but you will bless! They have arisen and been put to shame, but your servant will be glad!'</b> — the contrast: the accusers curse; YHWH blesses. Their cursing activity contrasts with the divine blessing. 'They have arisen and been put to shame' (<i>qamu vayevoshu</i>) — the enemy's rising (in accusation and attack) leads to their own shame. 'Your servant will be glad' (<i>avdecha yismach</i>) — David identifies himself as YHWH's servant (<i>eved</i>): the servant's joy is the outcome of divine vindication.</p>", "29": "<p><b>'May my accusers be clothed with dishonor; may they be wrapped in their own shame as in a cloak!'</b> — the return to the clothing metaphor from vv18-19: the accusers who clothed themselves with cursing are now clothed with 'dishonor' (<i>bushah</i>, shame). 'Wrapped in their shame as in a cloak' (<i>vaya'atu veyivoshu vaya'atu kem'il boshatam</i>) — the double clothing in shame. The elegance of the reversal: the garments they chose are returned to them.</p>", "30": "<p><b>'With my mouth I will give great thanks to the LORD; I will praise him in the midst of the throng'</b> — the thanksgiving vow: 'with my mouth' (<i>befi</i>) — the same mouth that has prayed and pleaded will give thanks when deliverance comes. 'In the midst of the throng' (<i>betokh rabbim</i>) — public, communal thanksgiving. The personal crisis that began with false accusation ends with public vindication; the congregation witnesses the conclusion.</p>", "31": "<p><b>'For he stands at the right hand of the needy one, to save him from those who condemn his soul to death'</b> — the psalm's theological conclusion. The accuser stood 'at the right hand' of the accused (v6: the adversary's position in court). Now YHWH stands at the right hand of 'the needy one' (<i>la'evyon</i>) — the same position, but as defender rather than prosecutor. The divine advocate takes the position of the accuser and reverses the accusation. 'Condemn his soul to death' (<i>shofte naphsho</i>, those who judge his soul) — the ultimate condemnation that YHWH overturns. The psalm that began with silence (v1: 'do not keep silence!') ends with YHWH actively standing in the place of human need.</p>"}, "110": {"2": "<p><b>'The LORD sends forth your mighty scepter from Zion. Rule in the midst of your enemies!'</b> — the divine sending of the royal scepter (<i>matteh uzzecha</i>, the scepter of your strength) 'from Zion' — the temple-city as the locus of divine sovereignty. The king's authority originates from YHWH's sanctuary, not from military conquest. 'Rule in the midst of your enemies' (<i>redeh beqerev oyevecha</i>) — dominion maintained not in safe territory but surrounded by opposition. The Davidic king reigns while enemies remain; the eschatological king will reign until all enemies are subdued (1 Cor 15:25).</p>", "3": "<p><b>'Your people will offer themselves freely on the day of your power, in holy garments; from the womb of the morning, the dew of your youth will be yours'</b> — 'offer themselves freely' (<i>amcha nedavot beyom chelecha</i>) — the volunteer army motif: <i>nedavot</i> (free-will offerings/volunteers) who come willingly on the 'day of power' (the day of battle). 'Holy garments' (<i>behadre qodesh</i>) — the priestly-military language: the armies come as a holy assembly. 'Dew of your youth' (<i>tal yaldutecha</i>) — the mysterious closing image: youthful vigor as fresh as the morning dew, suggesting an inexhaustible supply of warriors, or the king's own eternal youth.</p>", "4": "<p><b>'The LORD has sworn and will not change his mind, You are a priest forever after the order of Melchizedek'</b> — the most theologically significant verse of the psalm. YHWH swears an oath (<i>nishba YHWH velo yinachem</i>) — the unconditional nature of the Davidic covenant underscored by divine oath. 'Priest forever after the order of Melchizedek' (<i>kohen leolam al divrati Malki-Tzedek</i>) — the king is simultaneously priest, in the lineage of Melchizedek (the pre-Levitical priest-king of Salem: Gen 14:18-20). Hebrews 5-7 develops this text as the definitive argument for Jesus's high priesthood: Melchizedekian priesthood is superior to Levitical priesthood because it is royal, eternal, and not bound to the Levitical genealogy.</p>", "5": "<p><b>'The Lord is at your right hand; he will shatter kings on the day of his wrath'</b> — 'at your right hand' — in v1 the king was invited to sit at YHWH's right hand; here YHWH himself is 'at your right hand' (the defensive, protective position). The relationship is mutual: the king at YHWH's right as honored guest; YHWH at the king's right as protector. 'Shatter kings' (<i>machatz melachim beyom apo</i>) — the divine warrior's judgment on the kings of the nations who resist the Melchizedekian king. The language of eschatological judgment.</p>", "6": "<p><b>'He will execute judgment among the nations, filling them with corpses; he will shatter chiefs over the wide earth'</b> — the cosmic scope of the judgment: 'among the nations' (<i>bagoyim</i>), 'over the wide earth' (<i>rosh al-eretz rabbah</i>) — no geographic limit. 'Filling them with corpses' (<i>male geviyot</i>) — the battlefield carnage of comprehensive victory. 'Shatter chiefs' (<i>machatz rosh</i>) — the destruction of enemy leadership. Rev 19:11-21 (the rider on the white horse, the eschatological victory) draws on this psalm's divine-warrior imagery.</p>", "7": "<p><b>'He will drink from the brook by the way; therefore he will lift up his head'</b> — the psalm's final verse is the most cryptic. 'Drink from the brook by the way' (<i>minachal baderekh yishteh</i>) — possibly an image of the divine warrior pausing briefly mid-campaign to refresh himself, indicating the ease of the victory (no extended siege, no long campaign). 'Lift up his head' (<i>al-ken yarim rosh</i>) — the lifted head is the posture of victory and confidence (cf. Ps 3:3). The psalm that opened with the invitation to sit at YHWH's right hand closes with the triumphant lifting of the head — from the honored seat to the victorious field.</p>"}}

if __name__ == '__main__':
    book = 'psalms'
    source = 'mkt-context'
    existing = load_comm(source, book)
    merge_comm(existing, NEW_DATA)
    save_comm(source, book, existing)
    for ch, vv in NEW_DATA.items():
        saved = existing.get(ch, {})
        missing = [v for v in vv if v not in saved]
        print(f'  ch {ch}: {len(vv)} entries, {len(missing)} missing after merge')
